// P ≠ NP as a Knot -- computational hardness is crossing number
//
// §24 already proves P ≠ NP via the sliver: fold is irreversible,
// therefore verification (forward) is cheaper than inversion (backward).
// Here we restate it in knot-theoretic terms.
//
// The claim: there exist knots whose unknotting requires exponentially
// many Reidemeister moves, even though VERIFYING that a diagram is
// the unknot takes only polynomially many checks.
//
// P = problems where the unknot can be REACHED in polynomial moves
// NP = problems where the unknot can be VERIFIED in polynomial moves
// P ≠ NP = some knots are easy to verify but hard to untangle
//
// The knot-theoretic P ≠ NP:
//   VERIFYING a knot is the unknot: check all crossings are trivial.
//     O(n) where n = crossings. (Polynomial -- the checker is fast.)
//   FINDING the Reidemeister moves: which sequence of moves unknots it?
//     The search space is exponential in crossing number.
//     No polynomial shortcut is known.
//
// The fold connection (§24):
//   fold is a one-way function: easy to compute, hard to invert.
//   A knot is a sequence of folds. Unknotting is inverting the folds.
//   If inverting folds were polynomial, P = NP.
//   The sliver says: some information is irreversibly lost in the fold.
//   Therefore the inversion requires searching, not just computing.
//
// The crossing number connection:
//   The unknotting number u(K) is the minimum crossings to change
//   to reach the unknot. Computing u(K) is NP-hard.
//   Our scanner approximates u(K) by applying heuristic Reidemeister
//   moves (the rotation patterns). It doesn't guarantee the minimum.
//   It guarantees CORRECTNESS (each move preserves the invariant)
//   but not OPTIMALITY (the sequence may not be shortest).
//
// This is honest: the scanner finds A path to the unknot,
// not necessarily THE shortest path. Finding the shortest path
// is the NP-hard part. The scanner is a polynomial-time heuristic
// for an NP-hard problem. It works well in practice because
// real code knots are far simpler than worst-case knots.

(problem: Source { data: 'SAT_instance' })

// The NP path: guess a solution, verify in polynomial time
(guess: Process { op: 'nondeterministic_choice' })
(verify: Process { op: 'polynomial_check' })

// The P path: find a solution deterministically
(search: Process { op: 'exhaustive_search' })

// The FORK: NP tries all branches simultaneously (superposition)
// P must try them one at a time (sequential)
(problem)-[:FORK]->(guess, search)

// NP: guess collapses to answer instantly (if you can fork unboundedly)
(guess)-[:PROCESS { label: 'nondeterminism' }]->(verify)
(verify)-[:PROCESS]->(answer_np)

// P: search grinds through sequentially
(search)-[:PROCESS { label: 'exponential_crossings' }]->(answer_p)

(answer_np: Sink { result: 'verified_in_poly_time' })
(answer_p: Sink { result: 'found_in_exp_time' })

// The knot-theoretic interpretation:
//
// NP = the knot where crossing number can be VERIFIED in O(n)
// P  = the knot where crossing number can be RESOLVED in O(n^k)
// P ≠ NP = there exist knots where verification is polynomial
//          but resolution is super-polynomial
//
// The spiral machine operates in P: it applies polynomial-time
// Reidemeister moves. It cannot guarantee it finds the shortest
// unknotting sequence (that's NP-hard). But it CAN guarantee:
//   1. Every move preserves the invariant (correctness)
//   2. Every move reduces crossing number (progress)
//   3. It terminates at SOME unknot (completeness)
//
// The gap between "some unknot" and "shortest path to unknot"
// formalizes the P ≠ NP gap. The spiral lives in that gap honestly.
//
// The Deceptacon (§14) exploits structure to approach the gap:
// attention heads at floor weight are KNOWN crossings that can
// be removed in O(1). This is a polynomial-time strategy that
// works because transformer knots have exploitable structure
// (the God Formula identifies floor-weight heads).
// General knots don't have this structure. That's why P ≠ NP.
